AB  - As the Great Recession has unfolded in the United States, Occupiers, Tea Partiers, and even the Congressional Budget Office have brought discussion of economic inequality and government intervention to the forefront. An examination of polls focused on inequality, taxes, and mobility conducted between 1990 and 2011 reveals that American public opinion has remained fairly stable on these issues, despite changing political and economic conditions. Though subtle responses to events are evident, such as slightly greater support for income taxes, there have been no dramatic shifts of public opinion on these issues. Economic inequality, the government's role in redistribution, and taxation policies will likely remain divisive political issues in coming years in light of no decisive evolution of public opinion on how to address growing economic inequality. Adapted from the source document.
